---
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
---

<p-slide class="two-columns">
  <div>
    <h5 class="center">
      🛠️ <span class="main-gradient">what we write</span>
    </h5>
    <pre
      class="small-line"
      data-label-file="_palette.scss">
<code is:raw class="language-scss">$primary-500: #3b5bdb;
$steps: 100 200 300 400 500 600 700 800 900;
$step: 8%;
 
:root {
  @each $s in $steps {
    $i: index($steps, $s) - 5;
    --primary-#{$s}: #{mix(
      if($i < 0, white, black),
      $primary-500,
      abs($i) * $step
    )};
  }
}</code>
    </pre>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h5 class="center">
      🧊 <span class="main-gradient">what ships</span>
    </h5>
    <pre
      class="small-line"
      data-label-file="palette.css">
<code is:raw class="language-scss">:root {
  --primary-100: #dbe1f8;
  --primary-200: #b7c3f1;
  --primary-300: #94a5ea;
  --primary-400: #6f86e2;
  --primary-500: #3b5bdb;
  --primary-600: #2f49af;
  --primary-700: #233783;
  --primary-800: #182558;
  --primary-900: #0c122c;
}</code>
    </pre>
  </div>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      This is the world everyone in the room lives in. Don't mock it — recognise
      it.
    </p>
    <p>
      Left: one base + a Sass loop — the relationship IS described,
      declaratively.
    </p>
    <p>
      Right: the compiler flattens it into 9 dead values. The rule is gone, only
      frozen output ships.
    </p>
    <p>
      The point: the relationship existed in our source — the build just threw
      it away.
    </p>
    <p>No solution yet. Let them nod: "yep, that's my setup".</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h4 class="center" style="margin-block-end: 1.2em">
    🎨 <span class="main-gradient"
      >"Can you lighten the primary in the badges?"</span
    >
  </h4>

  <div class="hand-drawing center mid-dimension">
    <div p-fragment>
      <span data-box style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.4em">
        ✏️ tweak <span class="main-sub-gradient">lightenStep</span> in the config
      </span>
    </div>

    <div p-fragment>
      <span data-arrow data-down></span>
      <span data-box style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.4em">
        🔁 regenerate · build · deploy · review
      </span>
    </div>

    <div p-fragment>
      <span data-arrow data-down></span>
      <span data-box style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.4em">
        👀 <span>"mmh... too much"</span> &nbsp;→ &nbsp;start over (×4)
      </span>
    </div>

    <div p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      <span data-arrow data-down></span>
      <span data-box style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.4em">
        ⏱️ <span class="bold">2 hours</span> for an <span
          class="main-sub-gradient">8%</span
        > lightness shift
      </span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Same old world. A one-line intent ("lighten the badges") costs a full
      pipeline run.
    </p>
    <p>Let the boxes drop one by one. The room feels the loop tightening.</p>
    <p>Full pause before "2 hours". That's the punchline. Don't rush it.</p>
    <p>
      Still NO solution shown. The relief comes later — you have to earn it.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide class="center">
  <h5 class="main-gradient" style="line-height: 1.3em">
    How much of our design system's complexity exists because CSS couldn't do it
    —
  </h5>
  <h5
    p-effect="from below"
    style="line-height: 1.3em; margin-block-start: 0.4em"
  >
    and how much because we <span class="main-sub-gradient">stopped asking</span
    >
    whether it can now? 🤔
  </h5>

  <PNotes>
    <p>This is THE question of the talk. Let it land in silence.</p>
    <p>
      Second half enters from below: wait until it's on screen before reading
      it.
    </p>
    <p>Long pause after "?". Then cut to the title slide.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
